  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "For the task of object detection in traffic scenarios, three metrics are used to evaluate the performance of the detection algorithms: detection speed measured in frames per second (FPS), accuracy, and recall.",
    "The most commonly used metric is average precision (AP), which is derived from accuracy and recall.AP is usually evaluated in a class-specific manner, calculated separately for each object class.",
    "In order to compare performance across all object classes, the mean accuracy across all object classes (mAP) is used as the final measure of performance [90][91][92].",
    "The terminology of the metrics used to evaluate the performance of object detection algorithms is explained in the following section.IoU (Intersection over Union) is the ratio of the area of overlap between the predicted bounding box (BB predict) and the ground truth bounding box (BB ground) to the combined area of the two boxes.It uses the concept of the Jaccard exponent to calculate the similarity between these two sets.",
    "Figure 2 illustrates the concept of IoU, which has a value between 0 and 1, with closer to 1 indicating more accurate detection."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "In order to compare performance across all object classes, the mean accuracy across all object classes (mAP) is used as the final measure of performance [90][91][92]."
  ]
